      <td style="text-align: left; vertical-align: top;">
      <font color="#339999" face="Impact" size=+4>Laboratory for Computational<br>
      Biology and Bioinformatics</font>
      <P>
      <br>
      <!--                              -->
      <!-- start material for page here -->
      <!--                              -->
      <em>
      Welcome to the Laboratory for Computational Biology and Bioinformatics.<br>
      The Laboratory was started in June 2006 by Professor
      <a href="http://people.epfl.ch/bernard.moret">Bernard Moret</a>,
      Our main area of interest is the design of models and algorithms for
      problems arising in biology, mostly evolutionary biology (phylogenetics)
      and genomics (regulatory, comparative, and evolutionary genomics). We
      work mainly with large-scale simulations, but we also make use of
      published data, including most common databases in genomics and
      proteomics.
      </em>
      <br><br>
      <h3>
<font face="Trebuchet MS" color="#336666">Objective</font></h3>
      <font color="purple"><em>To design, implement, test, and assess
models and algorithms for discrete problems arising in evolutionary
molecular biology.</em></font>
      <br>
      <h3><font face="Trebuchet MS" color="#336666">Latest Publications and Presentations</font></h3>
      <ul>
        <font size=-1>
        <li> Lin, Y., and Moret, B.M.E., "A new genomic evolutionary
models for rearrangements, duplications, and losses that applies across
eukaryotes and prokaryotes", <em>Proc. 8th RECOMB Workshop on
Comparative Genomics <A HREF="http://recombcg.uottawa.ca/recombcg2010/">RECOMB-CG'10</A></em>,
in <A HREF="http://www.springer.com/computer/bioinformatics/book/978-3-642-16180-3"><em>Lecture Notes in Computer Science</em> <strong>6398</strong></A>, 228-239 (2010).</li>
        <li> Lin, Y., Rajan, V., and Moret, B.M.E., "Fast and accurate
phylogenetic reconstruction from high-resolution whole-genome data and
a novel robustness estimator", in <em>Proc. 8th RECOMB Workshop on
Comparative Genomics <A HREF="http://recombcg.uottawa.ca/recombcg2010/">RECOMB-CG'10</A></em>,
in <A HREF="http://www.springer.com/computer/bioinformatics/book/978-3-642-16180-3"><em>Lecture Notes in Computer  Science</em> <strong>6398</strong></A>, 137-148 (2010).</li>
        <li> Pattengale, N.D., Swenson, K.M., and Moret, B.M.E.,
"Uncovering hidden phylogenetic consensus", in <em>Proc. 6th Int'l
Symposium on Bioinformatics Research and Applications <A HREF="http://www.cs.gsu.edu/isbra10/">ISBRA'10</A></em>,
in <A HREF="http://www.springer.com/computer/bioinformatics/book/978-3-642-16180-3"><em>Lecture Notes in Computer Science</em> <strong>6053</strong></A>, 128-139 (2010).</li>
        </font>
      </ul>
      <h3><font face="Trebuchet MS" color="#336666">Latest Events</font></h3>
      <ul>
        <font size=-1>
        <li> Xiuwei Zhang travels to New York in November to give a
poster and an invited oral presentation at the <a
 href="http://recombsat.c2b2.columbia.edu/">7th RECOMB Conference on
Regulatory Genomics</a>. </li>
        <li> Alisa Yurovsky travels to Hong Kong in December to present
a paper at the <a href="http://www.math.hkbu.edu.hk/BIBM2010/">4th
Int'l Conference on Bioinformatics and Biomedicine</a>. </li>
        </font>
      </ul>
      <h3><font face="Trebuchet MS" color="#336666">Courses</font></h3>
      <font size=-1>We regularly teach the Master's level courses
      <em>Computational Molecular Biology</em> (Spring semesters, 5 EPFL
      credits) and <em>Advanced Algorithms</em> (Fall semesters, 7 EPFL
      credits).   We occasionally teach the PhD level course <em>Theory of
      Computation</em> (5 EPFL credits). We have co-taught (with colleagues
      from the School of Life Sciences) courses in Bioinformatics at both
      Master's and PhD level.</font>
      <h3><font face="Trebuchet MS" color="#336666">About EPFL</font></h3>
      <font size=-1>EPFL is consistently ranked first in Europe and among the
      world's top 20 in Engineering and Computer Science; see, for instance,
      the <A HREF="http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=414302&c=1">Times Higher Education</A>,
      the <A HREF="http://socialsciences.leiden.edu/psychology/students/news/leiden-ranking-2010-cwts.html">Leiden University ranking</A>, and the Shanghai Jiaotong <A HREF="http://www.arwu.org/">Academic Ranking of World Universities</A>.
     (Note that most rankings of Computer Science departments are unusable, as
     most rely on journals publications or on ISI Web of Science (which is
     heavily biased towards journals), whereas the high-value outlets in
     Computer Science are mostly conference proceedings.)</font>
